defer schedules its body to run as the enclosing scope exits, in reverse order
of registration. The emitter has no responsibility for that ordering - Swift's
runtime handles it - so we only emit the textual 'defer { ... }' form. defer is
legal in any block scope (function bodies, if branches, switch cases) and the
emitter does not specialise on enclosing context; the indent depth carried in
the context is sufficient to produce correctly nested output everywhere defer
appears.
@End Reasoning
