@Reasoning:
do-catch is Swift's structured error handling primitive. Inside the do-block any
'try' expression that throws transfers control to the matching catch clause; the
catch list is exhaustive against the throwing function's error type. We emit
'do { ... }' first and append catch clauses without a separating newline so the
canonical 'do { ... } catch { ... }' layout is preserved. The trailing newline
is emitted by THIS function, not by generate_catch_clauses, because callers
expect a single line break after the entire do-catch construct.
